Microsoft 365 Security Hardening Playbook

The 50 Security Controls Every Microsoft 365 Tenant Should Have

This playbook defines baseline security controls that should exist in every Microsoft 365 environment. These controls align with:
	•	Microsoft Zero Trust architecture
	•	Microsoft security baselines
	•	Microsoft Defender recommendations
	•	Identity-first security principles

⸻

Security Control Categories

The controls are grouped into the following domains:
	1.	Identity Security
	2.	Privileged Access Security
	3.	Conditional Access
	4.	Email Protection
	5.	Defender Security
	6.	Device Security
	7.	Data Protection
	8.	Logging & Monitoring
	9.	External Collaboration Security
	10.	Incident Response & Resilience

⸻

1. Identity Security (Entra ID)

Use identity as the primary security boundary.

Controls
	1.	Enforce Multi-Factor Authentication for all users
	2.	Require MFA for all administrators
	3.	Enable Microsoft Authenticator passwordless sign-in
	4.	Disable legacy authentication protocols
	5.	Enable Identity Protection risk policies
	6.	Require phishing-resistant authentication for admins
	7.	Enable Self Service Password Reset
	8.	Enforce strong password policies
	9.	Restrict user consent to applications
	10.	Monitor service principals and app registrations

⸻

2. Privileged Access Security

Administrative accounts are the highest risk identities.

Controls
	11.	Limit Global Admins to fewer than 5 accounts
	12.	Implement Privileged Identity Management (PIM)
	13.	Require Just-In-Time admin access
	14.	Create break-glass emergency accounts
	15.	Protect break-glass accounts with long passwords and exclusions from CA
	16.	Require MFA for privileged roles
	17.	Monitor privileged role assignments
	18.	Separate admin and user accounts
	19.	Use dedicated admin workstations
	20.	Enable privileged access reviews

⸻

3. Conditional Access

Conditional Access is the core enforcement engine of Zero Trust.

Controls
	21.	Require MFA for all cloud applications
	22.	Require MFA for privileged roles
	23.	Block legacy authentication
	24.	Require compliant devices
	25.	Require trusted locations for admin access
	26.	Block high-risk sign-ins
	27.	Block high-risk users
	28.	Require session controls for risky sign-ins
	29.	Require MFA for guest access
	30.	Require device compliance for SharePoint and OneDrive

⸻

4. Email Security (Exchange Online + Defender for Office 365)

Email is the primary entry point for attackers.

Controls
	31.	Enable Safe Links
	32.	Enable Safe Attachments
	33.	Configure anti-phishing policies
	34.	Enable impersonation protection
	35.	Enable mailbox intelligence
	36.	Enable external email warnings
	37.	Configure anti-malware policies
	38.	Implement SPF, DKIM, and DMARC
	39.	Block automatic forwarding to external domains
	40.	Enable user phishing reporting

⸻

5. Microsoft Defender Security

Defender provides threat detection and response across identities, endpoints, and email.

Controls
	41.	Enable Defender for Office 365
	42.	Enable Defender for Endpoint
	43.	Enable Defender for Identity
	44.	Enable Defender for Cloud Apps
	45.	Configure Automated Investigation and Response

⸻

6. Device Security (Intune)

Device trust should be part of access control.

Controls
	46.	Require device compliance policies
	47.	Require disk encryption
	48.	Require endpoint detection and response
	49.	Enforce security baselines
	50.	Require OS patch compliance

⸻

7. Data Protection (Purview)

Protect sensitive data regardless of where it lives.

Recommended Controls
	•	Sensitivity Labels
	•	Data Loss Prevention
	•	Retention Policies
	•	Insider Risk Monitoring
	•	Information Protection

⸻

8. Logging & Monitoring

You cannot detect attacks without visibility.

Required Logging

Enable:
	•	Unified Audit Logs
	•	Sign-in Logs
	•	Conditional Access Logs
	•	Defender Alerts
	•	Mail Flow Logs
	•	Admin Activity Logs

Recommended:
	•	Export logs to Microsoft Sentinel

⸻

9. External Collaboration Security

External sharing can expose sensitive data if not controlled.

Controls
	•	Restrict guest access
	•	Require MFA for guests
	•	Control SharePoint external sharing
	•	Monitor guest activity
	•	Expire unused guest accounts

⸻

10. Incident Response & Resilience

Security is incomplete without response capability.

Controls
	•	Create incident response procedures
	•	Enable automated investigation and response
	•	Enable alert notifications
	•	Implement SIEM monitoring
	•	Maintain security runbooks

